name: HOI WAH
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began the sport in her youth in Canada. (bwfbadminton.com, 01 Jan 2016)'), ('Reason', 'Badminton was a family recreation activity. (bwfbadminton.com, 01 Jan 2016)'), ('Debut', '2005 for Hong Kong, China (bwfbadminton.com, 01 Jan 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Zhong Teng Fu (hk01.com, 03 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia, and win a medal at the Olympic Games. (bwfbadminton.com, 01 Jan 2016; hk01.com, 06 Jul 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning gold at the 2015 Australian Open Superseries event. (bwfbadminton.com, 01 Jan 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCANADA TO HONG KONGShe was born in Hong Kong, China, and brought up in Canada, where her family lives. "After high school, my family sent me to [People\'s Republic of] China to train. I wanted to experience high intensity training and see if I still wanted to play. I spent a year in China and loved it. I met the Hong Kong head coach and he asked if I wanted to represent Hong Kong. My first answer was no because I wanted to go home! He asked me to think about it and I said I would talk to my parents. They decided that I should grab the opportunity. Of course I miss my family. I visit them in Canada once a year and I wouldn\'t be here without them." (bwfbadminton.com, 28 Jan 2016)NATIONAL FIRSTShe and Lee Chun Hei were the first mixed doubles pair from Hong Kong, China, to win a World Superseries title when they triumphed in the 2015 Australian Open in Sydney, NSW, Australia. She said that playing with Lee had helped her mature as a player. "[Playing] with Lee Chun Hei, I have learned a lot, maybe because I\'m now older and more experienced. I\'m forced to be more mature, and I have to be more assertive and honest with myself. If I\'m criticising my partner and not correcting myself, there\'s going to be a problem. My observations during gameplay are more mature than before. This is the big difference." (bwfbadminton.com, 28 Jan 2016; incheon2014.kr, 04 Oct 2014; hongkongsport.org, 26 Apr 2015; scmp.com, 31 May 2015) '), ('Nickname', 'Cathy (incheon2014.kr, 04 Oct 2014; hongkongsport.org, 24 Apr name: CAMILLE LILY MEI
bio: [('Beginning', "She began swimming at around age nine, when she and her family moved to Beijing, People's Republic of China. (calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016)"), ('Reason', '"I just loved swimming, hanging out with friends, being part of a sport." (scmp.com, 13 May 2016)'), ('Debut', '2013 for Hong Kong, China (swimswam.com, 22 Dec 2015)'), ('Awards', 'She received the Coach Wick Leadership Award while at the University of California, Berkeley in the United States of America. (calbears.com, 22 May 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFAMILY BACKGROUNDHer father is from Chinese Taipei, and her mother is from France. She was born in Hong Kong, China and attended the French International School, until her family moved to Beijing, People\'s Republic of China, when she was nine. (scmp.com, 13 May 2016; calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016)UNIVERSITY CLASSDuring her senior year at the University of California, Berkeley she led a two-credit class on female student-athlete leadership at the School of Public Health. Each Thursday she held the class, with about 30 student-athletes attending. "The first couple of weeks I wanted to get to know the class and create a safe environment for people to start talking. The goal is for the students to engage with these speakers, ask questions and gain tools that they can use with their teams and learn more about themselves as leaders." (scmp.com, 13 May 2016; calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016)LEADERSHIPShe was team captain while at the International School of Beijing between 2009 and 2011. She was also co-captain during her senior year at the University of California Berkeley. "I\'ve learned leadership. There are a million definitions for that, but I came in thinking I\'m not a leader. I can\'t be captain. I\'ve learned more about myself, what my strengths are, what my weaknesses are and how can I elevate my strengths to be a leader. I just think that everyone has something in them that they can contribute, and it\'s about bringing those traits out." (calbears.com, 22 Jan 2016; swimswam.com, 22 Dec 2015) '), ('Hero', 'US swimmer Natalie Coughlin. (hk.on.cc, 08 Jul 2016)'), ('Nickname', 'Camel (Instagram profile, 23 Jun 2016)'), ('Education', 'Psychology - University of California, Berkeley, United States'), ('Languages', 'English, French, Mandarin'), ('Highlights', "RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games34 x 100m Freestyle Relay2014Incheon, KOR3:39.9434 x 200m Freestyle Relay2014Incheon, KOR8:04.556100m Freestyle2014Incheon, KOR56.187200m Freestyle2014Incheon, KOR2:02.06Olympic GamesHeats50m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA25.92Heats100m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA54.92Heats200m Freestyle2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA1:59.71HeatsWomen's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2016Rio de Janeiro, BRA4:03.85World ChampionshipsHeats200m Freestyle2015Kazan, RUS2:00.96Heats4 x 100m Freestyle Relay2015Kazan, RUS3:42.11Heats4 x 200m Freestyle Relay2015Kazan, RUS8:06.51HeatsWomen's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2015Kazan, RUS4:04.54")]

name: MAN WAI VIVIAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began fencing in 2005 at age 11. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016; fie.org, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She tried a number of sports, including dancing and taekwondo, before finding fencing. "I was interested in taekwondo and so I did it all the way until I was age 11 and I got my black belt. But then my mother still wanted me to dance and in between she made me do ice skating. I liked it, but I was not so good at it. And then my father stepped in and said, \'Why don\'t you try fencing?\' Fencing is like the ballet of sports, it is very elegant. I really, really liked fencing so I started it at age 11." (fie.org, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Debut', '2008 for Hong Kong, China, World Cup in Nanjing, China (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Octavian Zidaru, ROU (scmp.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Training', 'She trains up to five hours a day. (scmp.com, 29 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Competing at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. name: YVETTE MAN-YI
bio: [('Beginning', 'She learned to swim at age three, and took up the sport competitively at age 11. (sportsoho.com, 13 Jun 2010)'), ('Reason', 'She enjoyed the direct competition of racing against other swimmers. (sportsoho.com, 13 Jun 2010)'), ('Awards', "She received the Potential Sports Star award [for swimming] at the 2009 Hong Kong Sports Stars Awards. (sportstar2013.hkolympic.org, 19 Nov 2013)She was named 2009 Most Improved Female Swimmer by the Hong Kong Swimming Coaches' Association. (hkswim.com, 18 Sep 2011)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralWUSHU HELPShe became a wushu national champion in 2018 and feels practising the sport has helped her swimming career "Practising wushu has helped me in different stages of my life. When I was young, it was like a form of expression for any active teenager and as I grew up and started serious training in swimming, it helped my back muscles. When I was more mature, it helped not only on the physical side but also the mental side, as wing chun focuses on close range movement and every step must be well-controlled and performed with great power. It helps you become more patient and to stabilise your mind, so that you know exactly what you are doing in every movement." (scmp.com, 16 May 2018)BATTLING DEPRESSIONShe battled with depression and quit the sport for three months in 2013. The mental anguish was so great she ran away from qualification meetings minutes before she was due to get in the pool. It was only after her coach Teri McKeever urged her to seek professional help, did she start to get to the root of her issues. "It seemed like a black hole I couldn\'t get out of, and I felt like I was in emotional pain. I felt numb. I kind of broke down and realised \'I can\'t do this\', at least swimming this way any more." (scmp.com, 28 Apr 2016) '), ('Education', 'Cognitive Science - University of California, Berkeley, United States'), ('Languages', 'Cantonese, English, Mandarin'), ('Highlights', name: HOI YAN JESSICA
bio: [('Coach', 'Shen Jinkang [national] (upower.com.hk, 16 Feb 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (sportsroad.hk, 31 Aug 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralTO SCOTLAND AND BACKBorn in Hong Kong, China, she grew up in Scotland after moving there as a girl. She attended university in Glasgow but in 2017 she decided to return to Hong Kong, China in order to pursue her dream of becoming a full-time athlete. She hoped the top class coaching and facilities would help give her the opportunity to compete on the international stage. "I am eager to be a full-time athlete and receive full-time training. I quit my job, sold my car, and said goodbye to my partner and my dog. I left behind a lot of things to come here, just to chase my dreams." name: Wai Hung
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up gymnastics at age six. (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)'), ('Reason', 'He was inspired to take up the sport after watching gymnastics on television. (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)'), ('Debut', '2004 for Hong Kong, China (FIG, 08 Jan 2010)'), ('Coach', 'Sergiy Agafontsev [national], UKR (singpao.com.hk, 01 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (hk01.com, 04 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning gold in men's vault at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (Facebook page, 17 Jul 2017; scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)"), ('Awards', 'In 2014 and 2015 he was named Gymnastics Sports Star of the Year by the Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, China. (scmp.com, 21 Mar 2016; sportstar2017.hkolympic.org, 01 Jan 2016)He was a torchbearer as the relay made its way through Hong Kong, China ahead of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (Facebook page, 05 Jun 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralLONDON DISAPPOINTMENTHe was unable to progress beyond the first round of the men\'s vault competition at the 2012 Olympic Games in London. He was so disappointed that he considered quitting the sport, but winning gold at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, went some way towards helping him erase the memory. "I wanted to die right there - all my hard work and effort over so many years disappeared in a flash. I have been haunted by that terrible moment for a long time. At one time, I even wanted to quit the sport. Even before the Incheon Games, I was still thinking about it. Hopefully, this success can help me forget it." (scmp.com, 27 Sep 2014)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first male gymnast to represent Hong Kong, China at an Olympic Games when he competed at the 2012 Games in London. "It\'s like a dream come true. I started training at the age of seven and going to the Olympic Games has always been my biggest ambition." (SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jul 2017; scmp.com, 12 Jan 2012) '), ('Hero', 'Chinese gymnast Zou Kai. (sportsroad.hk, 06 Aug 2014)'), ('Nickname', 'Stone (Facebook page, 05 Jun 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'He sustained ligament damage to his right shoulder while competing at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. He decided not to undergo surgery on the injury until after the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. name: SIU HONG
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began the sport at age six. (Athlete, 27 Jul 2010)'), ('Reason', 'He was inspired to take up the sport by his late father. "He was my source of inspiration. If not for him, I wouldn\'t have even learned to bowl." (ejinsight.com, 25 Nov 2015)'), ('Coach', 'Kim Eui-Young, KOR (hk.sports.appledaily.com, 10 Jan 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win gold at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (bka.mpweekly.com, 23 Dec 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the masters event at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (hongkongsport.org, 13 Apr 2015)'), ('Awards', 'He received a Hong Kong Sports Star Award in 2001, 2003, 2004, 2009, 2011, 2014 and 2015 from the Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, China. (sportstar2017.hkolympic.org, 01 Jan 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCANCER SURVIVORIn 2014, at age 29, he was diagnosed with testicular cancer, which had taken his father\'s life in 2011. After being cured through surgery and chemotherapy, he continued with his bowling career. "At first I could only bowl a score of 150, but I pressed on. I didn\'t disclose my condition to my team and coach until after the [2014] Asian Games. I didn\'t want them to worry about me and affect the morale of the team. Compared to what other people have gone through, my illness is minor. When my dad was diagnosed with cancer, he lived another three or four years. Life is so unpredictable. I really want to share my experience with children and other people; they need to know that they should treasure life." (scmp.com, 06 Dec 2015; bka.mpweekly.com, 23 Dec 2017) '), ('Hero', 'US tenpin bowler Parker Bohn III. (Athlete, 24 Nov 2006)'), ('Injuries', 'In December 2017 he was unable to compete at the Storm Cup in Seoul, Republic of Korea, due to a right hand injury.
